---
import SlidesLayout from '../../../layouts/SlidesLayout.astro';
const base = (import.meta.env.BASE_URL || '').replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<SlidesLayout
  title="Critical Thinking &amp; Clinical Judgment – Slides – D439 Foundations of Nursing"
  protected={true}
  backHref={`${base}/private/d439/critical-thinking`}
  backLabel="← Full Article"
>
  <div class="slides-wrapper">

    <!-- COLUMN 1: Title -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide slide-title">
          <div class="slide-badge">D439 – Foundations of Nursing</div>
          <div class="title-icon">🧠</div>
          <h1 class="slide-main-title">Critical Thinking &amp; Clinical Judgment</h1>
          <h2 class="slide-subtitle">NGN · Clinical Reasoning · NCLEX Review</h2>
          <p class="slide-note">← → Arrow keys or Prev / Next buttons to navigate · ↓ Arrow key for optional detail slides</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 2: Why CT Matters & NGN -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">2 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🎯 Why Critical Thinking Matters</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Critical thinking bridges knowledge and action — it's the foundation of safe, effective nursing care.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Why It Matters</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Patient safety</strong> — catches errors before they reach the patient</li>
                <li><strong>Complex patients</strong> — integrates knowledge across systems</li>
                <li><strong>Information overload</strong> — filters what's significant</li>
                <li><strong>Advocacy</strong> — recognizes when something is wrong</li>
                <li><strong>Ethical decisions</strong> — weighs competing values</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">NGN 6 Cognitive Skills</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Recognize cues</strong> — identify relevant data</li>
                <li><strong>Analyze cues</strong> — determine significance</li>
                <li><strong>Prioritize hypotheses</strong> — rank most likely/urgent</li>
                <li><strong>Generate solutions</strong> — identify expected outcomes</li>
                <li><strong>Take action</strong> — implement interventions</li>
                <li><strong>Evaluate outcomes</strong> — did it work?</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            💡 NGN tests <em>clinical judgment</em>, not rote recall. Think about what the data means, not just what it is.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 3: Crutch Teaching -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">3 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🦯 Crutch Teaching (NGN Q1)</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Apply critical thinking to patient teaching: assess first, then teach systematically.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Crutch Measurement</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Tip: <strong>6" lateral, 2" anterior</strong> to foot</li>
                <li>Top: <strong>2–3 finger-widths below axilla</strong></li>
                <li>Elbow: <strong>20–30° flexion</strong></li>
                <li>Formula: height – 16 inches</li>
                <li>Weight on <strong>hands</strong>, NOT axilla (nerve damage risk)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Gait &amp; Stairs</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Demonstrate gait on <strong>flat surface first</strong></li>
                <li>Stairs up: "Up with the <strong>good</strong>"</li>
                <li>Stairs down: "Down with the <strong>bad</strong>"</li>
                <li>Non-slip footwear required</li>
                <li>Check rubber tips for wear</li>
                <li>Written instructions + teach-back</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout">
            🔢 <strong>Teaching order:</strong> Assess strength/balance → explain → measure → demonstrate → return demo → stairs → safety → written → teach-back → document.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 4: Foley Catheter -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">4 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🩺 Foley Catheter (NGN Q2)</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro"><strong>Sterile technique</strong> required throughout. CAUTI is the most common healthcare-associated infection.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Female Insertion</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Position: dorsal recumbent</li>
                <li>Clean meatus: front-to-back, 3 swabs</li>
                <li>Non-dominant hand on labia = contaminated</li>
                <li>Insert <strong>2–3 inches</strong> until urine flows</li>
                <li>Advance 1 more inch, inflate balloon (10 mL)</li>
                <li>Pull back gently to resistance</li>
                <li>Secure to inner thigh</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Male Insertion</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Position: supine, penis at 90°</li>
                <li>Clean: circular motion outward, 3 swabs</li>
                <li>Insert <strong>7–9 inches</strong> until urine flows</li>
                <li>Advance 1 more inch, inflate balloon</li>
                <li>Replace foreskin if uncircumcised</li>
              </ul>
              <h3 class="col-title" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">CAUTI Prevention</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Remove ASAP, daily perineal care</li>
                <li>Bag ALWAYS below bladder level</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 5: Wound Stages -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">5 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🩹 Wound Stages (NGN Q3)</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">NPIAP Pressure Injury Staging — memorize each stage for NCLEX and clinical practice.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Pressure Injury Stages</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Stage I</strong> — non-blanchable erythema, intact skin</li>
                <li><strong>Stage II</strong> — partial thickness, shallow open ulcer or blister</li>
                <li><strong>Stage III</strong> — full thickness, subQ fat visible, may have slough</li>
                <li><strong>Stage IV</strong> — full thickness, exposed bone/tendon/muscle</li>
                <li><strong>Unstageable</strong> — obscured by slough or eschar</li>
                <li><strong>DTPI</strong> — deep purple/maroon non-blanchable area</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Wound Healing Phases</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Hemostasis</strong> — immediate (clot formation)</li>
                <li><strong>Inflammation</strong> — days 1–4 (redness/swelling/warmth = NORMAL)</li>
                <li><strong>Proliferation</strong> — days 4–21 (granulation tissue)</li>
                <li><strong>Maturation</strong> — 21 days – 2 years (~80% original tensile strength)</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="callout" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
                NEVER downstage a healing wound — healing doesn't reverse through stages.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 6: Culture & Assessment -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">6 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">🌍 Culture &amp; Assessment (Q7 + Q8)</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Cultural assessment is <strong>always the first step</strong> when caring for a patient from a different background.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Q7 — Cultural Assessment</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>Ask about beliefs, values, practices, preferences</li>
                <li>Food restrictions, modesty concerns</li>
                <li>Use trained medical interpreter (not family)</li>
                <li>Traditional medicine practices</li>
                <li>Decision-making style (individual vs. family)</li>
                <li>Spiritual/religious preferences</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Q8 — Assessment Quality</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><strong>Complete</strong> — all relevant data collected</li>
                <li><strong>Accurate</strong> — validated and verified</li>
                <li><strong>Objective</strong> — free from bias</li>
                <li>Open-ended questions first</li>
                <li>Active listening throughout</li>
                <li>Non-judgmental approach</li>
                <li>Collect BOTH subjective AND objective data</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            💡 Therapeutic relationship begins with the assessment — how you ask matters as much as what you ask.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COLUMN 7: Exam Tips -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide slide-exam">
          <div class="slide-number">7 / 7</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">📝 Exam Tips &amp; Key Points</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🧠</span><span class="tip-text">Critical thinking filters information for significance — not just facts</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">📊</span><span class="tip-text">NGN tests clinical judgment across 6 cognitive skills, not memorization</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🦯</span><span class="tip-text">"Up with the good, down with the bad" applies to ALL assistive devices</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🩺</span><span class="tip-text">Foley = sterile technique; weight on HANDS not axilla for crutches</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🩹</span><span class="tip-text">Stage I = intact non-blanchable skin; Stage IV = bone or tendon visible</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">🌍</span><span class="tip-text">Cultural assessment = FIRST step with diverse patient populations</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">❓</span><span class="tip-text">Open-ended questions invite elaboration; closed questions get yes/no</span></div>
            <div class="tip-card"><span class="tip-icon">✅</span><span class="tip-text">Teach-back confirms patient comprehension — not just "do you understand?"</span></div>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top:1.5rem; text-align:center;">
            <a href={`${base}/private/d439/critical-thinking`} class="article-link">← Full Article</a>
            <a href={`${base}/private/d439`} class="article-link article-link-ghost">D439 Home</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <style>
